#K-means clustering

Let’s start with an example of runing kmeans() function

# Generate some example data for clustering- rnorm generates random 30 points, here two groups 
tmp <- c(rnorm(30,-3), rnorm(30,3))
x <- cbind(x=tmp, y=rev(tmp))
plot(x)

##Hierarchical Clustering example

We must give the hclust() function a distance matrix not the raw data as input

#Distance matrix calculation 
d<- dist(x)

#clustering
hc<- hclust(d)

#plot results as a dendrogram
plot(hc)

plot(hc)
abline(h=6, col="red")

cutree(hc, h=6)

Another example, but more real life like with overlapping clusters of data

# Step 1. Generate some example data for clustering
x <- rbind(
matrix(rnorm(100, mean=0, sd = 0.3), ncol = 2), # c1
matrix(rnorm(100, mean = 1, sd = 0.3), ncol = 2), # c2
matrix(c(rnorm(50, mean = 1, sd = 0.3), # c3
rnorm(50, mean = 0, sd = 0.3)), ncol = 2))
colnames(x) <- c("x", "y")

# Step 2. Plot the data without clustering
plot(x)

# Step 3. Generate colors for known clusters
# (just so we can compare to hclust results)
col <- as.factor( rep(c("c1","c2","c3"), each=50) )
plot(x, col=col)

Q. Use the dist(), hclust(), plot() and cutree() functions to return 2 and 3 clusters

Q. How does this compare to your known ‘col’ groups?

#distance matrix calculation and clustering
hc <- hclust( dist(x))
#plot results as a dendrogram
plot(hc)
abline(h=2, col="red")
abline(h=2.8, col="blue")

# give results for 2 and 3 clusters
gp2 <- cutree(hc, k=2)
gp3 <- cutree(hc, k=3)

#PCA: Principal Component Analysis

We will use prcomp() function for PCA

## You can also download this file from the class website!
mydata <- read.csv("https://tinyurl.com/expression-CSV",
                   row.names=1)
#shows just first few row of data not all 
head(mydata, 10)

## gene2   219 200  204  210 187 427 423 434 433 426
## gene3  1006 989 1030 1017 973 252 237 238 226 210
## gene4   783 792  829  856 760 849 856 835 885 894
## gene5   181 249  204  244 225 277 305 272 270 279
## gene6   460 502  491  491 493 612 594 577 618 638

## gene8   175 182  184  166 180 255 291 305 271 269
## gene9   658 669  653  633 657 628 627 603 635 620
## gene10  121 116  134  117 133 931 941 990 982 934
nrow(mydata)
## [1] 100
ncol(mydata)
## [1] 10
colnames(mydata)
##  [1] "wt1" "wt2" "wt3" "wt4" "wt5" "ko1" "ko2" "ko3" "ko4" "ko5"
##Transposong the matrix , because prcomp reads it differnetly and running pca
pca <- prcomp(t(mydata), scale. = T)
## A basic PC1 vs PC2 2-D plot
plot(pca$x[,1], pca$x[,2], xlab = "PC1", ylab = "PC2")

Calculate the percent variance captures in each PC

## Precent variance is often more informative to look at
pca.var <- pca$sdev^2
pca.var.per <- round(pca.var/sum(pca.var)*100, 1)

head(pca.var.per)
## [1] 92.6  2.3  1.1  1.1  0.8  0.7
barplot(pca.var.per, main="Scree Plot",
xlab="Principal Component", ylab="Percent Variation")

## A vector of colors for wt and ko samples
colvec <- colnames(mydata)
colvec[grep("wt", colvec)] <- "red"
colvec[grep("ko", colvec)] <- "blue"
plot(pca$x[,1], pca$x[,2], col=colvec, pch=16,
xlab=paste0("PC1 (", pca.var.per[1], "%)"),
ylab=paste0("PC2 (", pca.var.per[2], "%)"))

Q5: Generating all pairwise plots may help somewhat. Can you make sense of the following code and resulting figure? What does it mean if a given point lies on the diagonal for a given plot? A: If sth is on a diagonal that means that the food is same

# Use the prcomp() PCA function 
pca <- prcomp( t(x) )
summary(pca)
## Importance of components:
##                             PC1      PC2      PC3       PC4
## Standard deviation     324.1502 212.7478 73.87622 4.189e-14
## Proportion of Variance   0.6744   0.2905  0.03503 0.000e+00
## Cumulative Proportion    0.6744   0.9650  1.00000 1.000e+00
#cumulative proportion means that letds say 96% of the data is captured in 2 dimensions 
mycols<- c("orange", "red", "blue", "darkgreen")

# Plot PC1 vs PC2
plot(pca$x[,1], pca$x[,2], xlab="PC1", ylab="PC2", xlim=c(-270,500))

#**colnames** names the points with country names
text(pca$x[,1], pca$x[,2], colnames(x), col=mycols)
